WEBVTT

00:00.100 --> 00:02.134
Previously on <i>Royal Pains...</i>

00:02.227 --> 00:04.227
Her father's on the way.

00:04.229 --> 00:05.478
No, he's already here.

00:05.480 --> 00:07.096
I'm the lucky dad.

00:07.098 --> 00:08.681
It turns out the source of your pain

00:08.683 --> 00:10.149
is not an ulcer at all,

00:10.151 --> 00:12.402
but a four-millimeter kidney stone.

00:12.404 --> 00:14.237
Nothing that small could cause
this much agony.

00:14.239 --> 00:15.605
This is your first day.

00:15.607 --> 00:16.856
I have the job?

00:16.858 --> 00:18.691
Unpaid internship.

00:18.693 --> 00:20.610
I thought I should add back
a little hydrocodone.

00:20.612 --> 00:23.079
How much do you need?

00:23.081 --> 00:26.532
Mr. Lawson, we would be happy
to consider your waiver.

00:26.534 --> 00:28.084
Okay. How long will that take?

00:28.086 --> 00:29.752
Six months to a year.

00:29.754 --> 00:32.622
I'm running for village council.

00:36.460 --> 00:39.462
[Orchestral music]

00:39.464 --> 00:39.964
♪

00:41.000 --> 00:47.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:53.727 --> 00:55.728
You were right. This guy's got flair.

00:55.730 --> 00:56.230
Shh!

00:59.734 --> 01:03.352
♪

01:03.354 --> 01:05.071
- Oh, look who's here.
- Shh!

01:05.072 --> 01:05.573
♪

01:15.031 --> 01:17.583
[Cell phone chime]

01:56.340 --> 02:00.426
Hey, don, I get the feeling
I'm a little late.

02:00.428 --> 02:02.595
Don't try
that lame "saving lives" excuse.

02:02.597 --> 02:04.213
Yeah, well, some of my patients actually

02:04.215 --> 02:06.516
- keep their appointments.
- Well, my bad. It's been busy.

02:06.518 --> 02:07.800
Are you doing okay, though?

02:07.802 --> 02:09.217
Yeah, no more kidney stones.

02:09.220 --> 02:10.586
Just been feeling a little tired.

02:10.588 --> 02:11.771
- Well...
- I know I'll reschedule

02:11.773 --> 02:13.356
- the follow-up.
- Tomorrow before work?

02:13.358 --> 02:15.191
Sure.

02:15.193 --> 02:16.642
Perfect.

02:16.644 --> 02:18.227
Looks like a good crowd tonight.

02:18.229 --> 02:19.812
Yeah, folks love this young guy.

02:19.814 --> 02:21.614
I don't know his music much,
but I admire

02:21.616 --> 02:23.816
what he does with at-risk kids.

02:23.818 --> 02:25.368
Speaking of...

02:25.370 --> 02:28.621
Say hello to Dr. Lawson, Molly.

02:28.623 --> 02:29.789
Hello, Dr. Lawson.

02:29.791 --> 02:31.040
Hello, Molly.

02:31.042 --> 02:32.608
Run along, Slack. She's got work to do.

02:32.610 --> 02:35.211
- All right, see you later.
- See ya.

02:35.213 --> 02:37.630
- Boy drives me nuts.
- His name is Slack?

02:37.632 --> 02:39.281
Yeah, it's a family name.
I assume they came over

02:39.283 --> 02:40.783
on the <i>Mayflower</i> and did nothing.

02:40.785 --> 02:42.218
[Chuckles]

02:42.220 --> 02:43.803
The boy's dad's in and out of jail,

02:43.805 --> 02:46.222
which wouldn't bother me,
except that we're neighbors.

02:46.224 --> 02:48.224
And the boy's always pestering my girl.

02:48.226 --> 02:50.309
Hey.

02:52.846 --> 02:55.898
- I try, Hank.
- I'll see you in the A.M.

02:58.519 --> 03:02.104
Paige. How lovely.

03:02.106 --> 03:03.573
Isn't it amazing?

03:03.575 --> 03:05.641
Yes. If it weren't for this migraine...

03:05.643 --> 03:07.994
I cannot survive the Rimsky-Korsakov.

03:07.996 --> 03:09.278
Oh, I'm so sorry.

03:09.280 --> 03:10.813
And such a week I have ahead.

03:10.815 --> 03:13.833
I have to oversee the packing of a...

03:13.835 --> 03:16.702
of an exquisite Chagall
that's off to auction...

03:16.704 --> 03:19.038
unless you'd like to take that on.

03:19.040 --> 03:21.007
A Chagall? Of course.

03:21.009 --> 03:22.925
The crating assistant
will meet you at 10:00.

03:22.927 --> 03:25.545
Tomorrow at 10:00?

03:25.547 --> 03:27.096
Inconvenient for you?

03:27.098 --> 03:30.349
No, no, it's just usually
I'm with Hankmed on mondays

03:30.351 --> 03:32.018
and with you...

03:32.020 --> 03:33.168
it's no problem.

03:33.170 --> 03:35.388
I'm on it.

03:35.390 --> 03:36.889
Bye.

03:38.976 --> 03:41.194
Hi. Two... black.

03:41.196 --> 03:43.696
Mr. Lawson... man of the hour.

03:43.698 --> 03:47.867
Ms. Ballard.
Why am I the man of the hour?

03:47.869 --> 03:49.518
You are running
for village council, aren't you?

03:49.520 --> 03:51.454
Against my appointment
for the open seat.

03:51.456 --> 03:54.207
Tara in the clerk's office
said you picked up a packet.

03:54.209 --> 03:56.459
She did? I asked her
not to mention that.

03:56.461 --> 03:58.711
Don't fret. You're new.

03:58.713 --> 04:00.213
I've lived here for over two years.

04:00.215 --> 04:01.831
Oh, dear, no, I meant new to politics.

04:01.833 --> 04:03.165
I'm sure you'll catch on.

04:03.167 --> 04:04.800
I'm impressed you think

04:04.802 --> 04:06.836
you can gather enough signatures
to get on the ballot

04:06.838 --> 04:08.721
on such short notice.

04:08.723 --> 04:10.389
Or one could pay a filing fee.

04:10.391 --> 04:14.209
Yes, you do have the option
to forgo public support,

04:14.211 --> 04:16.312
if that's the kind of candidacy
you want.

04:16.314 --> 04:17.930
[Laughs]

04:17.932 --> 04:19.932
Well, of course I'm getting signatures.

04:19.934 --> 04:21.733
200 should be a piece of cake.

04:21.736 --> 04:24.270
It's 300 for special elections...

04:24.272 --> 04:25.821
to discourage poseurs.

04:25.823 --> 04:27.723
We best get back.

04:27.725 --> 04:29.108
Good luck.
[Applause]

04:29.110 --> 04:30.743
Right.

04:32.779 --> 04:36.282
[Dramatic classical music]

04:36.284 --> 04:36.784
♪

04:56.970 --> 04:58.771
Aah!

04:58.773 --> 05:00.606
[Crowd gasps]

05:00.608 --> 05:02.141
Excuse me.

05:02.143 --> 05:04.393
Sorry. Excuse me.

05:04.395 --> 05:05.778
Excuse me. Coming through.

05:05.780 --> 05:07.262
[Grunts]

05:07.264 --> 05:09.865
Hi. Hi. I'm a doctor.

05:09.867 --> 05:11.567
- Are you okay?
- I'm fine.

05:11.569 --> 05:13.202
They finish playing. They work so hard.

05:13.204 --> 05:14.987
- Thank you.
- Are you all right?

05:14.989 --> 05:18.273
I'm okay. Let's go.
Okay, everybody, sit down.

05:18.275 --> 05:19.375
[Applause]
Come on. Come on.

05:19.377 --> 05:20.826
Hey, we can examine him afterwards.

05:20.828 --> 05:23.496
All right, Mussorgsky.

05:23.498 --> 05:26.115
[Playing <i>Night On Bald Mountain]</i>

05:26.117 --> 05:26.617
♪

05:58.415 --> 06:01.417
[Breathing heavily]

06:01.419 --> 06:04.870
♪

06:04.872 --> 06:07.206
[Coughs]

06:07.208 --> 06:07.708
♪

06:15.332 --> 06:16.332
[The Blue Van's <i>Independence</i> ]

06:16.357 --> 06:20.357
Royal Pains 5x05 - Vertigo
Original air date July 17, 2013

06:20.382 --> 06:21.872
Sync and corrections by atrn97g
for www.addic7ed.com

06:21.873 --> 06:24.092
The C.T. confirmed a minor concussion,

06:24.094 --> 06:25.543
but considering the fall he took,

06:25.545 --> 06:26.728
Santi was lucky.

06:26.730 --> 06:28.262
Oh, Santi.

06:28.264 --> 06:30.815
One ride to the hospital,
and she's on a nickname basis.

06:30.817 --> 06:33.101
Two rides, actually.

06:33.103 --> 06:34.936
I also gave Santi a lift

06:34.938 --> 06:36.821
to a patron's studio, where he's staying

06:36.823 --> 06:40.491
while the kids, you know, finish
their local concert dates.

06:40.493 --> 06:42.110
Thank you very much. And on to you.

06:42.112 --> 06:43.894
Is he as passionate in person?

06:43.896 --> 06:45.863
Wait a second.
Since when did classical dudes

06:45.865 --> 06:47.832
- get groupies?
- I'm not a groupie.

06:47.834 --> 06:49.066
I am a philharmonica.

06:49.068 --> 06:50.835
And, yes.

06:50.837 --> 06:53.004
I'm following up with him later today.

06:53.006 --> 06:54.206
Signing your sheet reminded me

06:54.207 --> 06:56.090
that I forgot to get his autograph.

06:56.092 --> 06:57.592
Thank you, guys, again

06:57.594 --> 06:59.761
for giving me the day off
to crate this painting.

06:59.763 --> 07:02.513
If Russel ever sends
our client's address.

07:02.515 --> 07:04.632
Nice. And on to you, Henry.

07:04.634 --> 07:07.351
If I sign this, does that mean
I'm obligated to vote for you?

07:07.353 --> 07:09.470
You're not, but you will.

07:09.472 --> 07:11.522
I don't know. What's in it for me?

07:11.524 --> 07:13.641
The convenience of seeing patients again

07:13.643 --> 07:14.859
in your home office.

07:14.861 --> 07:16.227
Way to pander to your base.

07:16.229 --> 07:17.779
Not bad, right?

07:17.781 --> 07:20.114
Bam! At this rate,
I'll be done by lunch.

07:20.116 --> 07:21.699
All right.

07:21.701 --> 07:24.068
We're out. See you guys.
[Cell phone chimes]

07:26.438 --> 07:28.456
What's wrong?

07:28.458 --> 07:30.708
I just got the client's address.

07:30.710 --> 07:32.943
So?

07:32.945 --> 07:35.379
Who is it?

07:35.381 --> 07:36.547
I don't understand.

07:36.549 --> 07:38.332
Like, Blythe Ballard Blythe Ballard.

07:38.334 --> 07:39.784
- Yes.
- No. No.

07:39.786 --> 07:42.053
No.

07:42.055 --> 07:43.387
Paige, no.

07:43.389 --> 07:46.624
You are absolutely not going
into that lioness' den.

07:46.626 --> 07:49.343
She...

07:49.345 --> 07:50.728
Wait a second.

07:50.730 --> 07:52.680
Hold on a second.

07:52.682 --> 07:54.232
This is perfect.

07:54.234 --> 07:55.600
You can be my eyes and ears.

07:55.602 --> 07:57.819
You can get inside
and expose her corrupt nature.

07:57.821 --> 08:00.905
Or I could be professional
and do my job.

08:02.140 --> 08:04.325
Or you could do that.

08:10.165 --> 08:13.000
It's not fair. I wasn't with Slack.

08:13.002 --> 08:14.168
You're just... you're seeing things.

08:14.170 --> 08:15.753
You ditched your community service.

08:15.755 --> 08:17.371
I took a break.

08:17.373 --> 08:18.589
No, you left! You left!

08:18.591 --> 08:20.591
It was a long break!

08:20.593 --> 08:22.760
- Ugh!
- Yeah, ugh!

08:22.762 --> 08:24.095
Bad time?

08:24.097 --> 08:26.848
Yeah. Yeah, it's called adolescence.

08:30.769 --> 08:32.669
Hey.

08:32.672 --> 08:34.889
Molly has some objections
to being grounded.

08:34.890 --> 08:38.442
Grounded on a boat...
it doesn't even make any sense.

08:38.443 --> 08:40.278
No TV.

08:40.280 --> 08:41.863
- Sorry to interrupt.
- Unh!

08:41.865 --> 08:45.233
Are you kidding? Please do.

08:45.235 --> 08:47.618
So you mentioned not feeling so great.

08:47.620 --> 08:49.070
What's up?

08:49.072 --> 08:52.290
Well, I'll stick to the medical.

08:52.292 --> 08:54.075
Probably best.

08:54.077 --> 08:56.861
Uh, I've been getting short
of breath when I exercise,

08:56.863 --> 08:58.579
a little weak and light-headed.

08:58.581 --> 09:01.165
I've been having some blurry vision.

09:01.167 --> 09:02.834
Any sharp abdominal pain?

09:02.836 --> 09:04.168
No, no, none of that.

09:04.170 --> 09:05.670
You still taking the diuretics
I prescribed

09:05.672 --> 09:06.971
after your kidney stone?

09:06.973 --> 09:08.472
Not happily, but, yeah.

09:08.474 --> 09:10.057
Well, good news...
I'm taking you off those.

09:10.059 --> 09:12.310
The symptoms you mentioned
could all be side effects

09:12.312 --> 09:13.644
from those water pills.

09:13.646 --> 09:15.263
And since you're having
no more issues...

09:15.265 --> 09:18.266
Oh, thank God.
I hate taking those pills, man.

09:18.268 --> 09:20.601
Sorry, doc.
I know that meds get a bad rap,

09:20.603 --> 09:22.854
but I just... I still hate 'em.

09:22.856 --> 09:25.055
No, look, I get it.

09:25.057 --> 09:27.191
I had a surgery last winter,
and afterwards I couldn't stand

09:27.193 --> 09:28.776
to look at those pills by my sink.

09:28.778 --> 09:30.661
Just knowing they were mine,

09:30.663 --> 09:32.663
it was depressing.

09:32.665 --> 09:34.198
Are you okay now?

09:34.200 --> 09:35.833
I am.

09:35.835 --> 09:39.537
And you're off all the meds?

09:39.539 --> 09:41.455
Yep.

09:41.457 --> 09:42.790
Okay.

09:48.263 --> 09:51.766
Well, your whole family
is full of surprises.

09:51.768 --> 09:54.752
I take it you work for Russel,
Ms. Lawson.

09:54.754 --> 09:58.589
I do, but, please,
Ms. Ballard, call me Paige.

09:58.591 --> 10:00.558
Please, Paige, call me Blythe.

10:00.560 --> 10:03.277
Blythe, if my assisting
with your artwork

10:03.279 --> 10:04.445
is uncomfortable for you...

10:04.447 --> 10:05.897
If I were to shun every neighbor

10:05.899 --> 10:07.565
with an issue before the council,

10:07.567 --> 10:08.983
I'd be a hermit.

10:08.985 --> 10:12.203
Don't tell me.
Russel has one of his migraines.

10:12.205 --> 10:14.322
Chicken.

10:14.324 --> 10:15.957
You want to see my baby?

10:15.959 --> 10:17.959
The Chagall? Yes.

10:17.961 --> 10:20.544
Very much.

10:22.748 --> 10:23.831
Wow.

10:23.833 --> 10:26.334
She's amazing.

10:26.336 --> 10:29.620
I don't know why I say "she."
It's both of them.

10:29.622 --> 10:31.505
It's Bella, Chagall's wife.

10:31.507 --> 10:33.474
He's lost in love.

10:33.476 --> 10:35.593
The painting was my grandmother's.

10:35.595 --> 10:38.980
In some ways, over the years,
I've mixed Bella up with grams...

10:38.982 --> 10:41.766
both strong women
who didn't surrender easily.

10:41.768 --> 10:45.302
But now I'm the one
who has to surrender her.

10:45.304 --> 10:48.940
It must be so intimate
to live with a piece like this,

10:48.942 --> 10:51.192
not just stand in front of it

10:51.194 --> 10:52.643
for a few minutes in a museum.

10:52.645 --> 10:54.829
When do your henchmen cart her away?

10:54.831 --> 10:57.248
Our packers should be here shortly.

10:57.250 --> 11:00.368
I will make sure your painting
is handled properly.

11:04.623 --> 11:06.007
Excuse me, sir?

11:06.009 --> 11:08.325
Hi. Could I just have
one moment of your time?

11:08.327 --> 11:11.178
I'm Evan R. Lawson,
and I'm collecting signatures

11:11.180 --> 11:13.547
to get on the ballot for a
vacancy on the village council.

11:13.549 --> 11:15.165
I'm gonna stop you right there.

11:15.167 --> 11:16.884
I spend summers here,
but I'm registered in the city.

11:16.886 --> 11:19.220
Oh. But you own a home here?

11:19.222 --> 11:21.188
- I do.
- Well, that's crazy.

11:21.190 --> 11:23.024
You own a home here, but you can't vote?

11:23.026 --> 11:24.191
Owning property
has nothing to do with voting,

11:24.193 --> 11:25.609
not since the 18th century.

11:25.611 --> 11:27.194
And you really can only vote
in one precinct.

11:27.196 --> 11:28.729
Oh, okay.

11:28.731 --> 11:31.032
Well, that's the first thing
I'll change, then.

11:31.034 --> 11:33.234
It's kind of in the constitution.

11:33.236 --> 11:35.403
And if it's any consolation,
after this little chat,

11:35.405 --> 11:36.904
I wouldn't have voted for you anyway.

11:36.906 --> 11:38.239
See, kids?

11:38.241 --> 11:41.459
That's why you do your homework
before video games.

11:41.461 --> 11:45.963
[Playing violin
along with recorded music]

11:45.965 --> 11:46.465
♪

11:53.673 --> 11:56.540
[Humming]

11:56.542 --> 11:59.877
Yah.

11:59.879 --> 12:02.430
[Volume increases]

12:02.432 --> 12:04.265
[Continues humming]

12:04.267 --> 12:06.067
[Knock at door]

12:06.069 --> 12:07.985
[Laughs]

12:07.987 --> 12:09.219
Come. Divya, you're early.

12:09.221 --> 12:10.738
No, I think I'm on time.

12:10.740 --> 12:12.890
Oh. Oh, please, just one moment.

12:12.892 --> 12:14.224
I'm not so used to this software.

12:14.226 --> 12:17.061
Ugh, I can't believe it's so late.

12:17.063 --> 12:18.562
I had a brainstorm before dawn,

12:18.564 --> 12:19.730
and I started composing.

12:19.732 --> 12:21.065
I should hit my head more often.

12:21.067 --> 12:23.250
As a medical professional,
I can't recommend that.

12:23.252 --> 12:27.288
Hmm. This wave came.

12:27.290 --> 12:30.424
It's, uh... an overture...

12:30.426 --> 12:31.842
I think. I don't know.

12:31.844 --> 12:33.243
It's something for the kids to rehearse

12:33.245 --> 12:34.261
on their European tour.

12:34.263 --> 12:35.629
I hate to tear you away

12:35.631 --> 12:38.015
for a post-concussive exam,
but I'll be brief.

12:38.017 --> 12:40.684
No, it's good. It's good to break.

12:40.686 --> 12:41.919
Any headaches or nausea?

12:41.921 --> 12:45.439
No. No, I feel, uh, inspired.

12:45.441 --> 12:47.858
Well, it's only fair.

12:47.860 --> 12:50.027
You've inspired so many others.

12:50.029 --> 12:52.530
Not to mention
all you give to your kids.

12:52.532 --> 12:53.948
Everybody says this, but, you know,

12:53.950 --> 12:55.699
it's the students that give to me.

12:55.701 --> 12:57.618
They are like sponges, you know.

12:57.620 --> 12:58.869
[Slurps]

12:58.871 --> 13:00.704
Well, you demand a lot of them.

13:00.706 --> 13:03.273
No, but it's the music
demands, you know?

13:03.275 --> 13:05.292
I mean, it's what my teacher gave to me.

13:05.294 --> 13:07.128
He knew the power of music.

13:07.130 --> 13:10.948
To pull a boy from El Cartucho,
the toughest streets in Bogota,

13:10.950 --> 13:13.384
and give to him a world...

13:13.386 --> 13:14.885
I can never repay this.

13:14.887 --> 13:16.804
Well, you do a fine job trying.

13:16.806 --> 13:18.756
And it seems that you've
sustained no lasting effects

13:18.758 --> 13:21.509
- from your fall.
- Oh, thank you.

13:21.511 --> 13:23.644
Sorry. Should I bring
the horns back later?

13:23.646 --> 13:25.396
No, no, no, it's okay.
I think we're finished.

13:25.398 --> 13:26.730
Divya, this is Lily.

13:26.732 --> 13:28.232
She is our orchestra's concertmaster.

13:28.234 --> 13:29.567
It's nice to meet you.

13:29.569 --> 13:30.518
I enjoyed your playing last night.

13:30.520 --> 13:32.136
Thank you. Is he okay now?

13:32.138 --> 13:34.321
- He is.
- Hey, everybody, we are leaving

13:34.323 --> 13:35.856
for Vienna on schedule.

13:35.858 --> 13:37.691
Ah, ha ha.

13:37.693 --> 13:39.243
As long as you stay podium-bound

13:39.245 --> 13:40.995
and don't try to fly again.

13:40.997 --> 13:42.329
No, but this is what I'm saying.

13:42.331 --> 13:44.281
If the music soars, then you must soar.

13:44.283 --> 13:46.650
You don't have a choice.
Then, please, soar with care.

13:46.652 --> 13:50.504
Divya, I appreciate everything
that you've done.

13:50.506 --> 13:55.209
I hate to be a gushing fan,
but I would love

13:55.211 --> 13:57.094
to get your autograph if I...
[Playing trumpet]

13:57.096 --> 14:00.181
Santi. Santi.

14:00.183 --> 14:01.832
What happened?

14:01.834 --> 14:04.552
I don't know. The room was like...

14:04.554 --> 14:06.687
Were you dizzy at all last night onstage

14:06.689 --> 14:07.771
before you fell?

14:07.773 --> 14:09.273
Why? What would it mean if I was?

14:09.275 --> 14:13.444
We'll need to run some tests
to find out.

14:16.666 --> 14:17.883
Yeah, I'm just checking in.

14:17.885 --> 14:20.419
Okay. Yeah, I'm spying.

14:20.421 --> 14:23.422
Look, I just want to make sure
that you stay grounded.

14:23.424 --> 14:25.391
[Coughs]
Yeah, or decked...

14:25.393 --> 14:27.226
whatever you want to call it, okay?

14:27.228 --> 14:29.345
I've got to go. Good-bye. Good-bye.

14:29.347 --> 14:31.347
[Coughs]

14:31.349 --> 14:32.932
Thanks for meeting me on my break.

14:32.934 --> 14:34.817
No problem.
Can I have your hand, please?

14:34.819 --> 14:38.520
Sounds like your shortness
of breath is worse

14:38.522 --> 14:40.656
and that Molly still
isn't cutting you and Slack.

14:40.658 --> 14:42.825
Sorry. Couldn't resist.

14:42.827 --> 14:43.943
I have to call her landline

14:43.945 --> 14:45.194
every couple hours to check up.

14:45.196 --> 14:47.696
Well, you know,
she could forward your landline.

14:47.698 --> 14:49.331
Aren't you supposed
to make me feel better?

14:49.333 --> 14:51.200
- Sorry again.
- No whip mocha.

14:51.202 --> 14:53.535
[Device beeping]
Yeah. You know, I try

14:53.537 --> 14:56.038
not to come down too hard
on Molly, but she keeps pushing.

14:56.040 --> 14:58.424
When her mom left,
Molly was only seven years old,

14:58.426 --> 15:01.326
and I thought she was gonna
act out, but she didn't.

15:01.328 --> 15:03.012
She was my rock.

15:03.014 --> 15:05.047
And then she hit her teens,
and I braced myself,

15:05.049 --> 15:07.049
but she stayed my sweet little girl...

15:07.051 --> 15:09.885
[Coughs]
up until this year.

15:09.887 --> 15:11.503
She's just so angry all the time,

15:11.505 --> 15:13.439
and it's like, she shuts me out.

15:13.441 --> 15:15.024
[Clears throat]

15:15.026 --> 15:17.476
I really miss her.
I miss us being a team.

15:17.478 --> 15:18.978
Well, I hear they come back.

15:18.980 --> 15:21.196
Yeah, if I can hang on that long.

15:21.198 --> 15:23.515
To that point, I want to follow up

15:23.517 --> 15:25.784
on your shortness of breath
and this cough you've developed.

15:25.786 --> 15:27.569
Plus, your oxygenation isn't great.

15:27.571 --> 15:30.022
Do you have time to get a chest
X-ray at Hamptons Heritage?

15:30.024 --> 15:31.707
I got a court appearance in an hour,

15:31.709 --> 15:33.125
and my car's in the shop.

15:33.127 --> 15:37.162
Well, how about I pick you up
when you're off duty?

15:41.051 --> 15:42.534
Quickly...

15:42.536 --> 15:44.553
- Go.
- Oh.

15:44.555 --> 15:47.039
- Any light-headedness?
- Mm, no.

15:47.041 --> 15:48.557
Actually, no, I just had a thought

15:48.559 --> 15:50.142
of adding violas to my theme.

15:50.144 --> 15:52.044
- Is that a symptom?
- Not to me.

15:52.046 --> 15:54.096
But I am partial to violas.

15:54.098 --> 15:56.348
- Did you play?
- In school.

15:56.350 --> 15:59.902
Pursuing music beyond that
was not practical.

15:59.904 --> 16:03.439
Hmm. I loved playing, though.

16:03.441 --> 16:05.074
Your parents didn't approve?

16:05.076 --> 16:07.192
No, it was me.

16:07.194 --> 16:09.161
I thought I needed
a more dependable career path.

16:09.163 --> 16:11.063
- Ah. Okay.
- Lie back again...

16:11.065 --> 16:12.898
Quickly...

16:12.900 --> 16:14.616
Go.

16:14.618 --> 16:18.236
Do you think that there's
some truth to musical talent

16:18.238 --> 16:19.538
being inherited?

16:19.540 --> 16:21.457
Oh, absolutely.

16:21.459 --> 16:23.292
Everyone in my family plays.

16:23.294 --> 16:24.626
The marimbas were always alive,

16:24.628 --> 16:25.928
and there was always dancing in my house

16:25.930 --> 16:27.212
ever since I was a baby.

16:27.214 --> 16:29.098
So then my child could be musical.

16:29.100 --> 16:30.582
You have a child?

16:30.584 --> 16:32.417
I meant one day.

16:32.419 --> 16:35.020
I believe you will pass
your love for music along.

16:35.022 --> 16:38.023
Hmm. So no nystagmus...

16:38.025 --> 16:40.926
- eye movement.
- So is that good or bad?

16:40.928 --> 16:43.028
Well, it rules out
benign positional vertigo...

16:43.030 --> 16:44.863
neither good nor bad, just puzzling,

16:44.865 --> 16:46.448
since it doesn't explain your dizziness.

16:46.450 --> 16:47.866
Okay.

16:47.868 --> 16:49.818
I'd like you to see an audiologist.

16:49.820 --> 16:51.153
Can it wait?

16:51.155 --> 16:52.738
I mean, we play Stony Brook tonight,

16:52.740 --> 16:54.323
and then we have two nights
in Manhattan,

16:54.325 --> 16:55.624
and then we go to Europe.

16:55.626 --> 16:57.876
What if I got you
an appointment this afternoon?

16:57.878 --> 17:00.712
Well, I mean, I could get Lily
to warm up the orchestra,

17:00.714 --> 17:02.831
but I have to be in white tie
and on the podium by 8:00.

17:02.833 --> 17:05.084
I'll see what I can do.

17:07.837 --> 17:09.338
Hi, there, guys.

17:09.339 --> 17:10.839
Could you give me
one second of your time?

17:10.840 --> 17:12.808
Okay. Thank you.

17:12.810 --> 17:15.227
All I need is one signature,
and I can get on the ballot. No?

17:15.229 --> 17:17.846
If I give you a little
tap dance, maybe sign it? Nope?

17:17.848 --> 17:19.431
Just one signature, sir, one signature.

17:19.433 --> 17:20.648
Please. My name's Evan R. Lawson.

17:20.651 --> 17:22.684
I'm begging you. Resident?

17:22.685 --> 17:23.935
Sir, are you a resident here?

17:23.938 --> 17:26.855
Ladies... I'm so sorry.

17:31.361 --> 17:33.112
No chance that you're
a resident here, is there?

17:33.114 --> 17:34.696
Born and raised.

17:34.698 --> 17:36.248
- Really?
- Yeah.

17:36.250 --> 17:37.533
Are you registered to vote?

17:37.535 --> 17:39.168
Dude, I haven't missed an election

17:39.170 --> 17:42.004
since I was 18 and wasted
my vote on Ralph Nader.

17:42.006 --> 17:43.088
[Laughs]

17:43.090 --> 17:45.323
Well, my name's Evan R. Lawson,

17:45.325 --> 17:47.042
and I'm running for village council.

17:47.044 --> 17:48.594
Oh, for Bostwick's seat, right?

17:48.596 --> 17:49.678
- Yeah.
- Nice.

17:49.680 --> 17:51.130
I heard the old dude retired.

17:51.132 --> 17:54.299
He did. But in with the new, right?

17:54.301 --> 17:55.834
You got it.

17:55.836 --> 17:57.686
I'm gathering signatures
so I can get on the ballot.

17:57.688 --> 17:59.221
- Yeah, hand it over.
- Really?

17:59.223 --> 18:01.807
Yep. So is this, uh...

18:01.809 --> 18:03.442
is this like a special election?

18:03.444 --> 18:06.228
That's exactly what it is.
You are very well informed.

18:06.230 --> 18:08.564
Well, I have to be.
I'm on the village payroll.

18:08.566 --> 18:10.616
So you're working with
Blythe Ballard, then, I guess.

18:10.618 --> 18:12.901
No, no, I'm running
against her candidate.

18:12.903 --> 18:15.954
Dude, I can't sign this.

18:15.956 --> 18:18.407
Ms. B... she's been great
for us lifeguards.

18:18.409 --> 18:20.159
She got us these chairs.

18:20.161 --> 18:22.711
Before that, I was out here
cooking in the sun all day.

18:22.713 --> 18:24.413
I got second-degree burns once.

18:24.415 --> 18:29.001
Speaking of which, you do have
some sunscreen on, right?

18:29.003 --> 18:31.336
- Yeah, I'm covered.
- Nice.

18:31.338 --> 18:34.339
- Thanks.
- Yeah. Good luck.

18:37.143 --> 18:39.478
I'm sorry if I called at a bad time.

18:39.480 --> 18:41.880
My lawyer can't call your lawyer.

18:41.882 --> 18:42.931
Bubbles facing out.

18:42.933 --> 18:44.483
36 years of marriage,

18:44.485 --> 18:46.401
and you're a total stranger to me.

18:46.403 --> 18:47.603
Go to the truck and get more tape.

18:47.605 --> 18:49.104
I've got plenty.

18:49.106 --> 18:51.389
Were you always this devious?

18:51.391 --> 18:52.891
Then take a break.

18:52.893 --> 18:54.326
If you really want
to hide assets from me,

18:54.328 --> 18:55.661
you should adopt your mistress.

18:55.663 --> 18:56.912
She's the right age.

18:56.914 --> 18:59.031
Franklin, did you hang up on me?

18:59.033 --> 19:01.700
- You did.
- We should be finished soon.

19:01.702 --> 19:05.787
Mr. Ballard is creating
financial problems for me.

19:05.789 --> 19:07.956
Which is why you have
to part with Bella?

19:07.958 --> 19:09.958
One really should be more careful

19:09.960 --> 19:13.345
when falling in love.

19:13.347 --> 19:15.080
Don't listen to me.

19:15.082 --> 19:17.432
I'm going through a bitter period.

19:17.434 --> 19:19.801
I'm sure you and Mr. Lawson

19:19.803 --> 19:21.386
will never have this kind of trouble.

19:21.388 --> 19:23.722
That's very sweet of you to say.

19:23.724 --> 19:27.609
Well done.

19:27.611 --> 19:31.697
No need for good-byes.

19:31.699 --> 19:33.365
Would you like
a little more time with her?

19:33.367 --> 19:35.817
We could come back in the morning.

19:39.489 --> 19:41.123
I hope this chest X-ray is clear.

19:41.125 --> 19:42.741
I don't have too many sick days left.

19:42.743 --> 19:44.493
I thought you were Superman
in your department.

19:44.495 --> 19:46.878
I don't take off for illness.
They're Molly crisis days.

19:46.880 --> 19:48.797
Or "molidays," as I like to call them.

19:48.799 --> 19:50.332
Well, you shouldn't worry
about the X-ray.

19:50.334 --> 19:51.750
I'm just being extra cautious.

19:51.752 --> 19:53.285
But if it is pneumonia,
[Cell phone rings]

19:53.287 --> 19:55.587
It's better to catch it early.
Speak of the devil.

19:55.589 --> 19:58.173
Molliwog, what's up?

19:58.175 --> 20:01.476
Whoa, whoa, slow down.
Where are you now?

20:01.478 --> 20:03.562
All right, listen to me.
Do not confront him.

20:03.564 --> 20:06.231
I'm on my way.

20:06.233 --> 20:07.599
Molly. Molly!

20:07.601 --> 20:09.067
- Where are we going?
- The marina...

20:09.069 --> 20:10.969
Slack's family boat.
His father has a gun.

20:10.971 --> 20:12.304
This is O'shea.

20:12.306 --> 20:15.107
Send all available units to the marina.

20:15.109 --> 20:18.443
Move back, folks.

20:18.445 --> 20:21.363
A family's being held
hostage on their boat...

20:21.365 --> 20:22.480
- shots fired.
- Where's my daughter?

20:22.482 --> 20:23.915
- Dad!
- No one has made contact

20:23.917 --> 20:25.033
with the father yet.

20:25.035 --> 20:26.201
He's drunk or high or something,

20:26.203 --> 20:27.586
and he's waving a gun around.

20:27.588 --> 20:29.504
I know. I know
I shouldn't have been there,

20:29.506 --> 20:31.123
- but I jumped off the stern...
- Listen, listen, you stay here

20:31.125 --> 20:32.341
with Hank, and you get
behind the car, you hear me?

20:32.343 --> 20:34.042
He pulled a gun on Slack's mom.

20:34.044 --> 20:35.427
Okay, I'm gonna take care of this.

20:35.429 --> 20:36.712
I'm gonna take care of it, all right?

20:36.714 --> 20:38.380
All right, Mike, Andy,
secure the perimeter.

20:38.382 --> 20:40.165
Give me all eyes on the boat. Let's go.

20:40.167 --> 20:41.883
All right, Molly, let's get
behind the car.

20:41.885 --> 20:44.303
Molly! Molly, stop!

20:57.617 --> 21:01.737
Terry, it's your neighbor Don.

21:01.739 --> 21:04.956
Listen, I'm a little concerned
about Rita and your son.

21:04.958 --> 21:06.491
Is everything okay in there?

21:06.493 --> 21:08.377
No, don, it's not okay!

21:08.379 --> 21:10.128
It's not my fault! Get out of here!

21:10.130 --> 21:11.696
No, no, no, no.

21:11.698 --> 21:13.332
It's okay. It's all right.
Your dad's got this.

21:13.334 --> 21:16.368
Hey, no, Terry.
No one's saying it's your fault.

21:16.370 --> 21:19.221
Listen, the bluefish are gonna
be coming in in a couple weeks.

21:19.223 --> 21:21.556
Weren't you and Slack
gonna take out the dinghy?

21:21.558 --> 21:24.426
He doesn't want to be with me.
He hates me.

21:24.428 --> 21:28.046
No. No, that's not true, Terry.

21:28.048 --> 21:30.849
I see the way Slack looks up to you.

21:30.851 --> 21:33.718
Now, listen, don't you think
you should let him come out?

21:33.720 --> 21:35.070
I do.

21:48.951 --> 21:51.086
Terry, are you there?

21:51.088 --> 21:54.373
Terry, are you still there? Talk to me.

21:54.375 --> 21:57.008
[Both sobbing]

21:57.010 --> 21:58.543
It's all right. Slack's okay.

21:58.545 --> 21:59.711
- Okay, Terry.
- Come on.

21:59.713 --> 22:01.513
All right, now I need you

22:01.515 --> 22:03.265
to put the gun down and come on out.

22:03.267 --> 22:05.016
Can you do that?

22:05.018 --> 22:06.518
Come on out.

22:10.223 --> 22:12.307
Hands! Show me your hands right now!

22:12.309 --> 22:13.692
Hands up! Hands up!

22:13.694 --> 22:15.310
Keep 'em up! Get down on your knees!

22:15.312 --> 22:17.312
Get down on your knees now! Cover me.

22:17.314 --> 22:18.930
- Is it over?
- It is. It is.

22:18.932 --> 22:21.099
He did it. He did it.

22:22.707 --> 22:24.708
Watch your head.

22:28.862 --> 22:30.696
Hey, Don...

22:30.698 --> 22:33.149
I noticed you were having
some trouble with your eyes.

22:33.151 --> 22:36.535
- You mind if I take a look?
- No, not at all.

22:36.537 --> 22:39.872
- Is the sunlight painful?
- Uh, a little bit, yeah.

22:41.575 --> 22:44.493
Then I apologize in advance
if this makes it worse.

22:44.495 --> 22:47.163
Open and look straight ahead.

22:47.165 --> 22:49.548
Mm.

22:49.550 --> 22:50.633
Bingo. What's that about?

22:50.635 --> 22:52.084
Photophobia...

22:52.086 --> 22:55.137
sensitivity to light
can have various causes.

22:55.139 --> 22:56.705
I'm also seeing red,

22:56.707 --> 22:59.675
not just around your irises but in them.

22:59.677 --> 23:03.262
And let's face it...
your vision was blurry before.

23:03.264 --> 23:05.147
You clocked that, huh?

23:05.149 --> 23:06.899
- I did.
- Yeah, well, if this doc thing

23:06.901 --> 23:08.684
doesn't work out for you,
you'll make a decent cop.

23:08.686 --> 23:10.102
Thank you very much.

23:10.104 --> 23:11.687
You have a swelling
and irritation of the eyes

23:11.689 --> 23:12.939
called uveitis.

23:12.941 --> 23:15.107
We'll treat it with anti-inflammatories,

23:15.109 --> 23:17.193
but we still need to determine
the root cause,

23:17.195 --> 23:18.411
and given your other symptoms,

23:18.413 --> 23:20.246
we really need to get that X-ray.

23:20.248 --> 23:22.999
Okay. Listen, thanks
for your help earlier.

23:23.001 --> 23:24.867
Yeah, you got it.

23:24.869 --> 23:27.920
Molly seems to have dealt well
with the trauma.

23:27.922 --> 23:29.956
Maybe she has her dad's ability
to take charge.

23:29.958 --> 23:32.758
Or like her dad, maybe she
just knows how to act tough.

23:32.760 --> 23:35.845
Listen, I'm gonna... I'm gonna go
be with her, okay?

23:35.847 --> 23:37.046
Yeah, yeah, yeah, of course.

23:37.048 --> 23:38.381
Your test can wait until morning,

23:38.383 --> 23:40.216
but call me if any new symptoms develop.

23:40.218 --> 23:41.801
- Thanks, doc.
- Sure.

23:46.523 --> 23:48.107
I'm sorry, Molly.

23:48.109 --> 23:50.109
I'll be on the boat.

23:52.696 --> 23:55.698
[Classical music playing loudly]

23:55.700 --> 23:58.701
[Music becomes whiny]

23:58.703 --> 23:59.203
♪

24:10.130 --> 24:12.081
Ah.

24:12.083 --> 24:13.165
I missed it.

24:13.167 --> 24:15.835
The audiologist? Yes, you did.

24:15.837 --> 24:17.253
I am so sorry.

24:17.255 --> 24:18.921
That is so rude,
after you made the effort.

24:18.923 --> 24:20.639
And you didn't answer your phone.

24:20.641 --> 24:21.807
I've been lost in this,

24:21.809 --> 24:23.459
and I have little to show for it.

24:23.461 --> 24:25.344
You know, it's not coming
like it sounds in my head.

24:25.346 --> 24:27.179
I thought maybe there's a glitch
or a problem

24:27.181 --> 24:29.815
with the subwoofer or something.

24:29.817 --> 24:32.101
Do you want to listen?

24:32.103 --> 24:34.070
Of course.

24:37.274 --> 24:41.160
[Classical music playing]

24:41.162 --> 24:41.662
♪

24:48.453 --> 24:49.919
It's very powerful.

24:49.921 --> 24:52.121
But it's tinny.

24:52.123 --> 24:54.206
There is no bottom to the music.

24:54.208 --> 24:55.758
Are you kidding?

24:55.760 --> 24:59.462
The timpani and the double bass
are overwhelming.

24:59.464 --> 25:00.679
They are?

25:00.681 --> 25:03.599
Wasn't there a tuning fork around here?

25:03.601 --> 25:04.717
Uh, yeah.

25:04.719 --> 25:06.719
But, uh, Divya, I don't have much time.

25:06.721 --> 25:08.504
I have to get dressed
for the concert tonight.

25:08.506 --> 25:10.606
It won't take long. Sit, please.

25:10.608 --> 25:14.060
Okay.

25:14.062 --> 25:15.861
- I want to try something.
- Okay.

25:15.863 --> 25:19.698
[Tuning fork humming]

25:19.700 --> 25:21.317
- Do you hear anything?
- Yeah.

25:21.319 --> 25:22.618
More in one ear or equally in both?

25:22.620 --> 25:23.786
It's more in the left ear.

25:23.788 --> 25:25.187
Okay.

25:25.189 --> 25:26.539
[Tuning fork humming]

25:26.541 --> 25:28.457
Nod when you can no longer
hear the tone.

25:28.459 --> 25:31.293
Okay.

25:31.295 --> 25:32.795
Yeah.

25:32.797 --> 25:34.046
[Tuning fork still humming]
Do you hear anything?

25:34.048 --> 25:37.049
No. What does that mean?

25:37.051 --> 25:39.385
You're experiencing
conductive hearing loss,

25:39.387 --> 25:40.920
especially in your left ear.

25:40.922 --> 25:43.872
So what you are saying...
the bass is there,

25:43.874 --> 25:45.057
but I just can't hear it.

25:45.059 --> 25:46.392
Mm-hmm.

25:46.394 --> 25:47.893
Will this get worse?

25:47.895 --> 25:49.878
We'll need to do a full workup
to answer that

25:49.880 --> 25:52.348
before going on tour.

25:54.101 --> 25:56.885
Could I, uh... can I go deaf?

25:56.887 --> 25:58.237
'Cause my students...

25:58.239 --> 25:59.721
you know, I won't be much of a mentor

25:59.723 --> 26:01.390
if I can't hear my students.

26:01.392 --> 26:03.442
I know that it's scary,

26:03.444 --> 26:05.444
but it's premature to be so dire.

26:05.446 --> 26:08.364
I'll have a list of names
of Manhattan ENTs for you

26:08.366 --> 26:10.082
by tomorrow morning.

26:10.084 --> 26:12.251
But, Santi, this appointment
you cannot miss,

26:12.253 --> 26:13.786
even if you get inspired.

26:13.788 --> 26:15.504
Maybe I shouldn't have wanted
so much to be

26:15.506 --> 26:16.956
in the company of Beethoven.

26:16.958 --> 26:19.408
If it's progressive,

26:19.410 --> 26:22.294
our treatment options
have also progressed quite a bit

26:22.296 --> 26:23.712
since Beethoven's day.

26:23.714 --> 26:26.382
[Inhales deeply]

26:26.384 --> 26:27.516
[Seagull cries]

26:27.518 --> 26:29.718
- How's it going, boss tweed?
- Hey.

26:29.720 --> 26:31.887
It's good. It's going great, actually.

26:31.889 --> 26:33.856
Yeah? That bad, huh?

26:33.858 --> 26:35.274
- Horrible.
- Ugh.

26:35.276 --> 26:37.610
I'm sorry. Man, you got some sun.

26:37.612 --> 26:38.894
Didn't you wear a hat?

26:38.896 --> 26:40.312
Politicians don't wear hats.

26:40.314 --> 26:41.564
They hide your eyes
and make you look shifty.

26:41.566 --> 26:42.948
Didn't you at least put on
some sunscreen,

26:42.950 --> 26:44.366
or does that make you
look slick and oily?

26:44.368 --> 26:45.484
I'm not an idiot, Henry.

26:45.486 --> 26:46.902
Of course I wore sunscreen.

26:46.904 --> 26:49.288
I've been reapplying it all day.
Oh, my God.

26:49.290 --> 26:51.040
Hydrating night cream?

26:51.042 --> 26:52.408
It's a very similar bottle.

26:52.410 --> 26:53.876
To your hydrating day cream?

26:53.878 --> 26:56.078
With SPF-40, yes. I have dry skin, okay?

26:56.080 --> 26:57.496
Can I talk to you seriously
for one second?

26:57.498 --> 26:59.965
I don't know.

26:59.967 --> 27:01.800
I'm having second thoughts
about my campaign.

27:01.802 --> 27:03.752
- Okay.
- Maybe running just to solve

27:03.754 --> 27:05.087
our Hankmed issue's a mistake.

27:05.089 --> 27:06.338
You mean a personal grudge

27:06.340 --> 27:08.591
isn't a solid political foundation?

27:08.593 --> 27:09.725
That's the thing.

27:09.727 --> 27:11.560
I know nothing about local issues.

27:11.562 --> 27:13.145
Evan, you've always been a quick study.

27:13.147 --> 27:15.347
I bet this night-cream mistake
doesn't happen twice.

27:15.349 --> 27:17.299
Sorry this took so long.

27:17.301 --> 27:18.734
Ah. Are you waiting tables, Stu?

27:18.736 --> 27:21.320
Oh, the joys of owning a business.

27:21.322 --> 27:23.189
Doc, don't tell me you're
running for village council.

27:23.191 --> 27:25.274
Uh, no, Evan is... I think.

27:25.276 --> 27:26.909
I guess I'll still serve you,

27:26.911 --> 27:30.196
even if you do join those
anti-business-zoning czars.

27:30.198 --> 27:32.865
Actually, I want to change
restrictive zoning laws.

27:32.867 --> 27:34.667
I've been trying to expand
for three summers,

27:34.669 --> 27:36.535
but those fossils on the council
want to keep

27:36.537 --> 27:38.120
the Hamptons in the last century.

27:38.122 --> 27:39.505
All they do is throw up roadblocks.

27:39.507 --> 27:41.173
That's exactly
why I want to get in there

27:41.175 --> 27:42.341
and shake things up.

27:42.343 --> 27:45.844
Well, you got my vote, pal.

27:45.846 --> 27:47.129
And, hey,

27:47.131 --> 27:48.964
food's on the house.

27:48.966 --> 27:50.432
- Thank you, Stu.
- Yes.

27:50.434 --> 27:51.850
Hey, folks, how's the day?

27:51.852 --> 27:53.852
I think I just got my first issue.

27:53.854 --> 27:55.521
I think you just got your first bribe.

27:55.523 --> 27:57.389
- I better eat this.
- It wasn't a bribe.

27:57.391 --> 27:58.691
I didn't promise him anything.

27:58.693 --> 28:01.610
Still, to be safe.

28:01.612 --> 28:03.062
Manhattan is going to flip.

28:03.064 --> 28:04.396
It's only for one night.

28:04.398 --> 28:06.031
Unless she changes her mind.

28:06.033 --> 28:10.736
It's just so sad
that she has to let Bella go.

28:10.738 --> 28:12.621
- Bella was Chagall's wife.
- Yes.

28:12.623 --> 28:13.989
You got an "A" in early modernists.

28:13.991 --> 28:15.241
How nice for you.

28:15.243 --> 28:18.026
You were supposed
to follow instructions.

28:18.028 --> 28:19.878
If I wanted someone
to get all emotional,

28:19.880 --> 28:21.247
I would have gone myself.

28:21.249 --> 28:23.415
You knew it would be tough.

28:23.417 --> 28:25.334
Heart-wrenching.

28:25.336 --> 28:27.803
So many clients treat their precious art

28:27.805 --> 28:29.204
as only investments.

28:29.206 --> 28:31.423
When someone actually appreciates

28:31.425 --> 28:35.010
what they have, I get all gooey.

28:35.012 --> 28:38.314
But you are not allowed to.

28:38.316 --> 28:40.516
Understood. I will take care of it.

28:40.518 --> 28:41.767
And I'm very sorry to have bothered you

28:41.769 --> 28:43.819
- during your migraine.
- Russel!

28:43.821 --> 28:47.022
We're out of Pinot!

28:47.024 --> 28:48.907
And there's my migraine.

28:48.909 --> 28:52.661
[Chuckles]
Okay.

28:54.948 --> 28:57.950
[Gentle violin music playing]

28:57.952 --> 28:58.452
♪

29:15.352 --> 29:18.053
[Humming]

29:18.055 --> 29:21.056
[Classical music plays]

29:21.058 --> 29:22.441
♪

29:22.443 --> 29:25.527
[Humming with music]

29:25.529 --> 29:26.029
♪

29:51.304 --> 29:55.007
- Divya!
- Santi?

30:02.788 --> 30:03.955
Santi.

30:03.957 --> 30:05.506
Divya, thank God you came.

30:05.508 --> 30:08.176
What happened... dizzy again?

30:08.178 --> 30:09.427
It's worse.

30:09.429 --> 30:13.298
I feel better now, but...

30:13.300 --> 30:16.134
- My voice... it hurts.
- Your throat?

30:16.136 --> 30:18.853
No, no, no, the sound of my voice...

30:18.855 --> 30:20.305
it hurts my ears.

30:20.307 --> 30:22.307
What were you doing when it started?

30:22.309 --> 30:24.776
Uh, I was taking a break.

30:24.778 --> 30:26.561
I was checking the mixer.

30:26.563 --> 30:29.030
Hey, I got your call.

30:29.032 --> 30:30.865
Yes. Sorry. I asked Hank to join us.

30:30.867 --> 30:33.117
I hear you've been having dizzy spells.

30:33.119 --> 30:35.570
It's horrible.
It's like the world is tilting.

30:37.990 --> 30:39.540
Okay, his vitals are normal.

30:39.542 --> 30:43.661
I'm beginning to suspect
Tullio phenomenon.

30:43.663 --> 30:45.830
It's a vertigo that is sound induced.

30:45.832 --> 30:48.449
When you were dizzy earlier,
the horns were playing,

30:48.451 --> 30:50.301
and this time you were mixing tracks.

30:50.303 --> 30:52.720
Do you feel up to testing
Divya's theory?

30:52.722 --> 30:55.790
- Sure. Yeah.
- Okay, good.

30:55.792 --> 30:57.392
[Grunts]
It's okay.

30:57.394 --> 30:58.726
Okay.
[Loud piano notes]

30:58.728 --> 31:00.678
Whoa.

31:00.680 --> 31:03.064
Looks like Divya's on the right track.

31:03.066 --> 31:05.233
It was much worse before.

31:05.235 --> 31:06.517
I'd like to try something else.

31:06.519 --> 31:08.603
- Can you sit down for me?
- Yeah, okay.

31:10.906 --> 31:12.990
Oh, ear plugs... perfect.

31:12.992 --> 31:15.309
I don't want you to hear the music.

31:15.311 --> 31:18.579
Santi, can you play back your
theme with just the violins?

31:18.581 --> 31:21.249
- Just the violins?
- Mm-hmm.

31:21.251 --> 31:24.001
Okay.

31:24.003 --> 31:27.038
[Violins playing]

31:27.040 --> 31:29.924
♪

31:29.926 --> 31:31.292
I'd like to take your pulse.

31:31.294 --> 31:32.710
Yeah.

31:32.712 --> 31:36.497
[Heart beating]

31:41.053 --> 31:43.354
Can you add the percussive hits now?

31:43.356 --> 31:45.306
Yeah.

31:45.308 --> 31:49.227
[Percussion and violin]

31:49.229 --> 31:52.313
Hank, watch his eyes.

31:52.315 --> 31:56.200
♪

31:56.202 --> 31:58.486
The hits match his blinking.

31:58.488 --> 32:02.323
And the strings
match the wave of his pulse.

32:02.325 --> 32:03.791
[Music stops]

32:03.793 --> 32:05.126
There are flutes that chirp.

32:05.128 --> 32:07.295
They could be in sync
with cranial pressure changes.

32:07.297 --> 32:08.963
A chirp... that's exactly the sound

32:08.965 --> 32:10.548
I was going for.

32:10.550 --> 32:11.883
Santi has been composing

32:11.885 --> 32:13.301
a theme he's been hearing
since his fall,

32:13.303 --> 32:15.035
but he has been having trouble focusing

32:15.037 --> 32:16.370
and losing track of time.

32:16.372 --> 32:18.639
I have been feeling cloudy, you know?

32:18.641 --> 32:20.641
Am I crazy to think that his composition

32:20.643 --> 32:22.393
could be based on autophony?

32:22.395 --> 32:23.845
No, his fall may have caused cracks

32:23.847 --> 32:25.563
in the temporal bone in his inner ear.

32:25.565 --> 32:27.265
Santi, I think that your music

32:27.267 --> 32:30.067
reflects bodily sounds
that you are literally hearing

32:30.069 --> 32:32.570
in your head because of a thin
or cracked ear bone.

32:32.572 --> 32:34.155
You've been hearing your blood pulse,

32:34.157 --> 32:35.940
your eyes moving in their sockets,

32:35.942 --> 32:37.825
maybe even the creak of your joints.

32:37.827 --> 32:40.194
Well, so much for inspiration.

32:40.196 --> 32:42.830
But wait. When we did the
C.T. scan for the concussion,

32:42.832 --> 32:44.282
it didn't show this?

32:44.284 --> 32:46.233
A C.T. wouldn't pick it up,
but there are hi-def scans

32:46.235 --> 32:48.169
that can confirm Divya's diagnosis.

32:48.171 --> 32:50.288
And a soft-tissue graft
can repair the damage.

32:52.407 --> 32:54.459
Will my hearing be fully restored?

32:54.461 --> 32:56.711
Yes. It will.

33:55.854 --> 33:58.105
Oh, uh, I was gonna wash my hands.

33:58.107 --> 33:59.640
Help yourself.

34:02.160 --> 34:04.161
Please don't feel too badly for me.

34:04.163 --> 34:05.663
I'm not so entitled I don't realize

34:05.665 --> 34:07.164
how fortunate I was
to have Bella's company

34:07.166 --> 34:09.033
for as long as I did.

34:09.034 --> 34:10.952
Nothing lasts forever.

34:10.954 --> 34:12.920
Blythe, where did you get this bowl?

34:12.922 --> 34:13.955
I have no idea.

34:13.956 --> 34:15.505
It's been in the family for years.

34:15.507 --> 34:17.208
Have you ever had it appraised?

34:17.210 --> 34:18.492
I never thought to.

34:18.494 --> 34:20.511
It's a sweet thing, isn't it?

34:20.513 --> 34:22.763
I always liked the glaze.

34:22.764 --> 34:25.466
Now, I could be wrong,

34:25.467 --> 34:28.351
but these marks look authentic to me.

34:28.353 --> 34:29.887
Authentic what?

34:29.889 --> 34:32.273
Song Dynasty ceramic.

34:32.275 --> 34:34.859
And not a chip or a crack in it.

34:34.860 --> 34:37.061
Would it have value at auction?

34:37.063 --> 34:39.313
Maybe more than Bella...

34:39.315 --> 34:41.032
maybe considerably more.

34:41.034 --> 34:42.366
We'll have to get an appraiser out,

34:42.368 --> 34:44.702
but in the meantime,
you should stop using this

34:44.704 --> 34:48.072
as a soap dish,
and I should stop the truck.

34:48.074 --> 34:49.824
You mean...

34:49.826 --> 34:52.460
Oh, Paige, how can I ever repay you?

34:57.165 --> 34:59.967
Those white areas
are swollen lymph nodes

34:59.969 --> 35:02.386
in the hilar region.

35:02.388 --> 35:03.638
Is that bad?

35:03.640 --> 35:05.222
Prednisone will help reduce
the swelling,

35:05.224 --> 35:08.175
and we'll keep you
on a preventative dose.

35:08.177 --> 35:11.095
Okay, so you're saying
it may come back, then?

35:11.097 --> 35:12.647
Yes.

35:12.649 --> 35:14.649
It could.

35:14.651 --> 35:16.601
This inflammation,
together with your eye symptoms

35:16.603 --> 35:19.737
and recent kidney stone,
suggests a serious condition

35:19.739 --> 35:21.489
called sarcoidosis.

35:21.491 --> 35:23.574
- Sarcoidosis?
- Yeah.

35:23.576 --> 35:25.276
It's treatable,
but a complicated disease

35:25.278 --> 35:27.411
because its course is hard to predict.

35:27.413 --> 35:29.997
Some people have one episode,
and it never reoccurs.

35:29.999 --> 35:31.499
Others suffer chronic bouts.

35:31.501 --> 35:34.234
So, if I'm in that second category,

35:34.236 --> 35:38.456
I may need to take some of those
sick days for myself, then.

35:38.458 --> 35:42.710
I'm afraid it's possible.

35:44.379 --> 35:46.464
Look at what Chewy's is up to now.

35:46.466 --> 35:48.966
Trying to sway public opinion
with freebies?

35:48.968 --> 35:50.768
- It could work.
- Yeah, with the takers.

35:50.770 --> 35:53.354
But those clams are killer.

35:53.356 --> 35:55.773
You're right.

35:55.775 --> 35:58.142
Okay, we'll take a sample.

35:58.144 --> 35:59.477
I'm sorry?

35:59.479 --> 36:01.779
"Free Chewy's."

36:01.781 --> 36:05.566
Oh. No. No, there's no giveaway.

36:05.568 --> 36:08.653
That's not a bad idea, though.
I'll have to tuck that one away.

36:08.655 --> 36:09.987
Uh, my name is Evan R. Lawson.

36:09.989 --> 36:11.605
I'm running for village council

36:11.607 --> 36:13.874
and in support of Chewy's expansion,

36:13.876 --> 36:15.109
which, I don't know if you know,

36:15.111 --> 36:16.544
but it's been thwarted again and again...

36:16.546 --> 36:17.962
That guy comes out here, brand-new...

36:17.964 --> 36:19.997
He doesn't get the Hamptons.

36:19.999 --> 36:21.916
He bought Chewy's six years ago.

36:21.918 --> 36:23.384
And wants to add a second story.

36:23.386 --> 36:24.885
To an historical landmark.

36:24.887 --> 36:26.120
All right, little-known fact...

36:26.122 --> 36:28.139
the original Chewy's had a second floor.

36:28.141 --> 36:30.257
It was blown away by hurricane Hazel

36:30.259 --> 36:31.425
in 1954.

36:31.427 --> 36:32.793
This would be a restoration.

36:32.795 --> 36:34.812
This guy wants to expand Chewy's.

36:34.814 --> 36:37.732
Actually, I want a fair
and open zoning waiver process.

36:37.734 --> 36:40.017
What's next... franchises
up and down the beach?

36:40.019 --> 36:41.819
No, the moratorium on new structures

36:41.821 --> 36:43.354
would not be affected at all.

36:43.356 --> 36:45.022
Until he gets a foot in the door.

36:45.024 --> 36:47.858
- Exactly.
- You believe this guy?

36:47.860 --> 36:51.245
I appreciate how thorough you've been,

36:51.247 --> 36:52.997
but I've got a favor to ask of you.

36:52.999 --> 36:54.365
- You bet.
- I'd like to keep

36:54.367 --> 36:55.616
this diagnosis between us.

36:55.618 --> 36:57.368
Oh, it's not my place to reveal it.

36:57.370 --> 36:59.003
I'd like to have your blessing

36:59.005 --> 37:03.207
in that I not share my condition
with my department yet.

37:03.209 --> 37:07.211
Since we don't know how
or even if it's gonna come back,

37:07.213 --> 37:09.346
I'd like to keep up my balancing act.

37:09.348 --> 37:12.133
If I have a flare-up,
you'll be my first call,

37:12.135 --> 37:13.884
the captain will be the next.

37:13.886 --> 37:15.269
Sounds like a plan.

37:15.271 --> 37:16.837
And with these chronic conditions,

37:16.839 --> 37:18.856
having a good plan is half the battle.

37:18.858 --> 37:22.059
I guess we all can't have
smooth recoveries like yours.

37:22.061 --> 37:23.861
- Yeah.
- I'll see you.

37:23.863 --> 37:25.479
You know, don, I misled you
the other day

37:25.481 --> 37:28.515
about being drug-free.

37:28.517 --> 37:30.484
The truth is, I'm still
on some pain medication

37:30.486 --> 37:32.853
that I thought I'd be off by now.

37:32.855 --> 37:35.790
But my recovery hasn't been that easy,

37:35.792 --> 37:37.992
and I guess it's hard
for me to admit it.

37:37.994 --> 37:41.796
Well, it sounds like neither
one of us can accept being sick.

37:41.798 --> 37:44.799
[Chuckles]

37:47.807 --> 37:50.637
It's like the whole town's
under Blythe's spell.

37:51.592 --> 37:53.626
Changing things
might be harder than I thought.

37:53.628 --> 37:55.794
Maybe I have good news.

37:55.796 --> 37:57.346
Oh, yeah? I need it.

37:57.348 --> 37:59.515
Blythe actually admitted
that she may have been

37:59.517 --> 38:03.636
a little overzealous
in her anti-Hankmed crusade.

38:03.638 --> 38:06.105
And since she knows
that politics isn't your thing,

38:06.107 --> 38:08.674
she offered to expedite
our zoning waiver

38:08.676 --> 38:09.942
so you can withdraw.

38:09.944 --> 38:11.110
She offered to make it go away?

38:11.112 --> 38:13.279
- Yeah.
- As long as I drop out?

38:13.281 --> 38:15.064
Well, she didn't say it like that.

38:15.066 --> 38:16.649
Well, of course she didn't, Paige.

38:16.651 --> 38:19.034
If she did, it would be a bribe.

38:19.036 --> 38:20.736
It'd be a naked bribe.

38:20.738 --> 38:22.238
She was trying to be nice.

38:22.240 --> 38:23.906
But she made it conditional, didn't she?

38:23.908 --> 38:26.041
She said, if she cleared things up,

38:26.043 --> 38:27.543
you wouldn't have to run.

38:27.545 --> 38:30.079
Oh, my God.

38:30.081 --> 38:31.664
What happened to "rules are rules"?

38:31.666 --> 38:33.716
Suddenly she's just playing favorites.

38:33.718 --> 38:35.334
You know what I think?

38:35.336 --> 38:38.137
I think she's threatened.

38:38.139 --> 38:41.223
Blythe Ballard is threatened by me.

38:41.225 --> 38:43.309
Okay, that's ridiculous!

38:43.311 --> 38:45.928
Sorry. I didn't mean
to sound so emphatic.

38:45.930 --> 38:47.513
Just think about it.

38:47.515 --> 38:49.181
She's used to getting
her own way all the time.

38:49.183 --> 38:50.482
She manipulates the council.

38:50.484 --> 38:51.901
She manipulated me

38:51.903 --> 38:53.903
into this whole
signature-gathering time suck,

38:53.905 --> 38:55.387
but this isn't about me anymore.

38:55.389 --> 38:57.889
What this town needs is dissent, Paige.

38:57.891 --> 39:01.577
It needs an outside voice.

39:01.579 --> 39:04.413
It needs me.

39:04.415 --> 39:05.998
Oh, boy.

39:08.084 --> 39:09.868
Your recovery will take a few weeks,

39:09.870 --> 39:11.453
but you should be back on your feet

39:11.455 --> 39:13.789
before your students
get back from Europe.

39:18.128 --> 39:19.428
What's this?

39:19.430 --> 39:21.913
This is the beginning of my composition

39:21.915 --> 39:24.433
with that autograph that you requested.

39:24.435 --> 39:27.019
Oh, my gosh. Thank you.

39:27.021 --> 39:28.771
I didn't think that you had heard.

39:28.773 --> 39:30.272
No, I heard. And you know what?

39:30.274 --> 39:32.024
Thanks to you, I will continue to hear.

39:32.026 --> 39:33.943
But honestly, Divya, look,

39:33.945 --> 39:36.312
I don't need this, uh, ear plugs.

39:36.314 --> 39:37.529
And the chair, it's...

39:37.531 --> 39:39.231
Uh, just in case.

39:39.233 --> 39:40.983
[Classical music playing]
What is this?

39:40.985 --> 39:44.036
What am I hearing?

39:44.038 --> 39:44.538
♪

40:00.670 --> 40:02.004
Bravo!

40:02.006 --> 40:03.756
<i>Bravissimo!</i>

40:03.758 --> 40:04.258
♪

40:14.684 --> 40:16.735
Hey.

40:16.737 --> 40:18.637
Was your sentence lifted?

40:18.639 --> 40:21.323
Yeah, served my time.

40:21.325 --> 40:23.108
What's wrong with my dad?

40:23.110 --> 40:25.611
You should ask him.

40:25.613 --> 40:28.414
I did. He blew me off.

40:28.416 --> 40:30.482
Look, you know,
even if something were going on,

40:30.484 --> 40:31.667
I couldn't tell you,

40:31.669 --> 40:33.419
just like I respected
your confidentiality.

40:33.421 --> 40:34.653
I can tell something's weird.

40:34.655 --> 40:35.954
He's, like, with you all the time.

40:35.956 --> 40:37.506
Yeah, we've gotten to be friendly.

40:37.508 --> 40:39.291
My dad doesn't have friends.

40:39.293 --> 40:40.509
All he does is work.

40:40.511 --> 40:41.710
And raise you.

40:41.712 --> 40:43.462
And keep secrets from me.

40:43.464 --> 40:45.014
He won't tell me anything.

40:45.016 --> 40:46.465
He's my father. I have a right to know.

40:46.467 --> 40:48.166
I understand.

40:48.168 --> 40:49.852
But you got to give your dad a break.

40:49.854 --> 40:54.473
And getting so angry doesn't help.

40:54.475 --> 40:58.894
Look, when I was growing up,
my mom had a rule...

40:58.896 --> 41:00.779
never go to bed angry.

41:00.781 --> 41:02.698
And it worked out pretty well for us.

41:02.700 --> 41:04.349
Yeah, let me guess, to this day,

41:04.351 --> 41:08.821
you and your mom are still best buddies?

41:08.823 --> 41:11.790
- Well, no.
- See? It's a stupid rule.

41:13.993 --> 41:17.963
My mom died...

41:17.965 --> 41:20.382
when I was younger than you are.

41:22.034 --> 41:24.002
My dad's not going to die.

41:24.004 --> 41:26.338
I didn't say he was.

41:28.425 --> 41:31.343
But I lost my mom way too soon.

41:31.345 --> 41:33.979
And if you waste the time
you have with your dad,

41:33.981 --> 41:36.231
pushing him away, you will regret it.

41:40.437 --> 41:41.987
You better not let him die.

41:41.989 --> 41:43.689
Again, I didn't say he was at risk.

41:43.691 --> 41:45.741
But if he were, I would do
everything I could to help him,

41:45.743 --> 41:47.576
I promise you that.

41:51.581 --> 41:53.165
Well...

41:53.167 --> 41:56.502
if he dies...

41:56.504 --> 41:58.036
it's your fault.

41:58.038 --> 42:01.090
[Melancholy pop music]

42:01.092 --> 42:01.592
♪

42:09.373 --> 42:17.373
Sync and corrections by atrn97g
